comments.text:
Imagine this. There is a man — no one knows his real name, they simply call him the Oppressor. Not just any tyrant, but one who crushes without mercy. He invades, steals, lies, and leaves families shattered. His victims cry out — for justice, for help, for the Ummah to hear them. Their homes are in ruins, their voices hoarse from screaming into silence.

“And what is [the matter] with you that you fight not in the cause of Allah and [for] the oppressed among men, women, and children who say, ‘Our Lord, take us out of this city of oppressive people...’” (Surah An-Nisa 4:75)

And yet… He does not stand alone. Around him are allies — not strangers, but those who once prayed beside the oppressed, those who call themselves part of the same Ummah. People who should be protectors of the weak, defenders of truth. But they look away. Or worse — they shake the hand of the Oppressor, make deals with him, and help him tighten his grip.
Why? Fear? Power? Dunya? Or have their hearts just grown cold?
“Indeed, those who conceal what We sent down of clear proofs and guidance... they are cursed by Allah and cursed by those who curse.” (Surah Al-Baqarah 2:159)

But not everyone turns away. There are a few — not powerful, not rich — just sincere believers with trembling voices and steady hearts. Distant members of the Ummah, perhaps, but close in spirit. They stand up. They give what little they have. They speak when others stay silent. And for this, they are mocked. Called idealists. Fools. "Too emotional." "Too naïve." Still, they rise.  They remember that the Ummah is like one body. They remember their duty:
“O you who have believed, be persistently standing firm in justice, witnesses for Allah, even if it be against yourselves or parents and relatives...” (Surah An-Nisa 4:135). “You are the best nation produced [as an example] for mankind. You enjoin what is right and forbid what is wrong and believe in Allah...” (Surah Aal-Imran 3:110)

And so they carry that pain — willingly. Because faith (iman) without action is empty. And in the darkest of nights, even one believer, holding the light of truth, is enough to remind the world what the Ummah was meant to be.
